📚 Book Sales Analysis Using SQL

A complete SQL project focused on analyzing a Book Sales Database to derive meaningful business insights related to books, customers, orders, inventory, revenue, and sales performance.

📌 Project Overview

This project demonstrates the use of SQL for solving real-world business problems in the publishing and retail industry. The database contains information about books, customers, and orders, enabling comprehensive analysis of sales trends, customer behavior, inventory management, and revenue generation.

The project covers SQL concepts ranging from basic filtering and aggregation to advanced joins, grouping, subqueries, and business analytics.

🗂️ Database Schema

The database consists of the following tables:

📖 Books

Stores information about available books.

Column	Description
Book_ID	Unique identifier for each book
Title	Name of the book
Author	Author of the book
Genre	Book category
Published_Year	Year of publication
Price	Selling price
Stock	Available inventory

👤 Customers

Stores customer information.

Column	Description
Customer_ID	Unique customer identifier
Name	Customer name
City	Customer city
Country	Customer country

🛒 Orders

Stores order transaction details.

Column	Description
Order_ID	Unique order identifier
Customer_ID	Customer placing the order
Book_ID	Purchased book
Quantity	Number of copies ordered
Order_Date	Date of purchase
Total_Amount	Order value

🎯 Project Objectives
Analyze book sales performance.
Identify customer purchasing patterns.
Track inventory and stock levels.
Measure revenue generation.
Discover top-selling books and genres.
Generate actionable business insights using SQL.

📊 Business Questions Solved
--Basic SQL Analysis--
1. Retrieve all books in the Fiction genre
Filtering data using WHERE.
2. Find books published after 1950
Date and numeric filtering.
3. List all customers from Canada
Customer segmentation by country.
4. Show orders placed in November 2023
Date filtering and extraction.
5. Retrieve total stock of books available
Inventory analysis using aggregate functions.
6. Find details of the most expensive book
Ranking and sorting records.
7. Show customers who ordered more than one quantity
Order behavior analysis.
8. Retrieve orders where total amount exceeds $20
High-value transaction analysis.
9. List all available genres
Distinct value retrieval.
10. Find the book with the lowest stock
Inventory monitoring.
11. Calculate total revenue generated
Revenue analysis using aggregation.
--Advanced SQL Analysis--
1. Total books sold for each genre
Sales performance across categories.
2. Average price of Fantasy books
Genre-based pricing analysis.
3. Customers with at least two orders
Customer loyalty analysis.
4. Most frequently ordered book
Best-selling product identification.
5. Top 3 most expensive Fantasy books
Advanced sorting and limiting.
6. Total quantity sold by each author
Author performance evaluation.
7. Cities where customers spent over $30
Geographic customer analysis.
8. Customer who spent the most
Highest-value customer identification.
9. Stock remaining after fulfilling all orders
Inventory management and stock forecasting.

